      "Psalm 31 is a lament of David under real pressure—slander, plots, and a body worn down by grief—that keeps circling back to trust in the Lord as rock and fortress. Its central line, “Into thine hand I commit my spirit” (v. 5), became Jesus’ own dying prayer (Luke 23:46) and Stephen’s under stoning (Acts 7:59), showing how deeply the church has leaned on this psalm in extremity. Henry traces its rhythm as complaint answered by renewed resolve: David names his affliction honestly, then talks himself back into confidence in God’s hand and God’s “times.” It reads as a template for suffering saints who anchor identity in God’s care rather than in their circumstances or critics.",
